main event: A radar target was observed at 170 dts, 50 miles away, with a ground speed of 3700 knots for six minutes at Gray AFB in Killeen, Texas on 30 August 1958. The observed target behavior was contrary to the normal characteristics of a radar target, possibly indicating an astronomical phenomenon or some other reflection target.
interesting points: The radar target traveled at a speed of 3700 knots, which is extremely fast for that time period.
The target was observed on Air-Intercept-Radar for two minutes, indicating it was not a momentary blip but a sustained observation.
The observed target behavior was contrary to the normal characteristics of a radar target, leading to difficulties in evaluating the phenomenon.
There was a significant radar fade within two minutes of observation, suggesting a sudden disappearance.
The observation was made by a 1st Lieutenant and a Senior Director at the 614th ACWRON, adding credibility to the witnesses.
witnesses: 1st Lieutenant and Senior Director at the 614th ACWRON
photographs: No photographs included in the report
